But as the minutely divided saline particles of the sulphur are very closely united to its sulphureous particles, it happens in tbe deflagration ol sulphur (when the sulphureous and nitro-aerial particles throw each other into fiery motion) that the saline particles of the sulphur, adhering to its sul- phureous particles, are by frequent impacts oi the nitro-aerial particles struck, rubbed, and comminuted, so that the saline particles from being often rubbed and pounded, are at last sharpened like small swords and are moreover so attenuated as to be changed from rigid and solid into flexible and fluid particles. The saline particles of the sulphur in lact which were previously of a fixed nature change, alter they are thus sharpened and made fluid, into an acrid and aeid liquid, and probably constitute the common spirit ol sulphur.

That the facts of the case are as stated may be inferred froma careful study of the flame of sulphur since it is very different from other flames. For nitro-aeria particles do not shine ruddily and glow in the flame ol burning sulphur as in other cases, but owing to their diminished motion appear blue, so that it would appear that some third substance is interposed between the nitro-aeria] and sulphureous particles, and that by it these fiery particles are hindered in their motion. For as the nitro-aerial and fiery particles, when in violent agitation, glow, so when their motion is retarded they appear of a blue colour. And this is the reason that the flame ol an expiring lamp is wont to be blue. But of this more else- where.
